  "The Belmont Report established:": "",
  "Statistical formulas for hypothesis testing": "",
  "Ethical principles for research with human subjects: respect, beneficence, and justice": "",
  "Standards for manufacturing quality control charts": "",
  "Methods for stratified random sampling": "",
  "The Belmont Report (1979) laid out three fundamental ethical principles: respect for persons, beneficence (minimizing harm), and justice (fair distribution of research burdens and benefits).": "",
  "P-hacking (trying many analyses until finding significance) is:": "",
  "Required by most IRBs": "",
  "Always acceptable if the sample is large": "",
  "A thorough approach to data analysis": "",
  "An ethical and methodological problem that inflates false positives": "",
  "P-hacking exploits random noise by testing many hypotheses until one produces a significant result, dramatically increasing the false positive rate.": "",
