  "Researchers should always agree with participants' opinions": "",
  "All participants must be treated identically regardless of circumstances": "",
  "Researchers should be respected by their institutions": "",
  "Individuals should be treated as autonomous agents and those with diminished autonomy deserve extra protection": "",
  "Respect for persons means acknowledging individuals' right to make their own informed decisions about participation, and providing additional protections for those with diminished autonomy.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company funds a study on its own drug and finds it is 30% more effective than competitors. However, the lead researcher owns $500,000 in company stock. An independent replication finds only a 5% difference. What ethical issue does this scenario illustrate?": "",
  "There is no ethical concern as long as the study was published": "",
  "A conflict of interest where the researcher's financial stake may have biased the original results": "",
  "The independent study must be wrong because it is smaller": "",
  "The company properly disclosed the conflict": "",
  "The researcher's significant financial interest in the company creates a conflict of interest that may have consciously or unconsciously influenced the study design, analysis, or reporting of results.": "",
  "A university psychology department wants to study how people respond to stress. They plan to tell participants they are taking a simple memory test, but will actually subject them to unexpected loud noises and time pressure to induce stress. Participants will be debriefed afterward. What ethical requirement must be met before this study can proceed?": "",
  "No requirements, since participants will eventually be debriefed": "",
  "Only the department chair needs to approve": "",
  "The study can proceed as long as participants sign a general consent form": "",
  "IRB approval is required because the study uses deception and could cause psychological distress": "",
  "Studies involving deception and potential psychological stress require IRB review to ensure the deception is justified, risks are minimized, and proper debriefing procedures are in place.": "",
  "A health researcher collects blood samples from 500 patients for a diabetes study. Five years later, she wants to use the stored samples to study a different genetic condition without contacting the patients for new consent. Is this ethically acceptable?": "",
  "No, because using samples for a different purpose than originally consented to violates informed consent principles": "",
  "Yes, because five years is long enough to reuse any data": "",
  "Yes, as long as the new study is also about health": "",
  "Yes, because she already has the samples": "",
  "Informed consent is specific to the study described to participants. Using samples for a different purpose without obtaining new consent or having a broad consent provision violates the principle of respect for persons.": "",
  "A researcher studying income inequality collects survey data including names, addresses, incomes, and social security numbers. The data is stored on an unencrypted laptop that is later stolen. Which ethical principle was most directly violated?": "",
  "Informed consent only": "",
  "Confidentiality and data security obligations": "",
  "The principle of beneficence": "",
  "Justice": "",
  "Researchers have an ethical obligation to protect participants' personal information through proper data security measures. Storing sensitive data unencrypted is a serious breach of confidentiality.": "",
  "A social media company uses data from its 2 billion users to conduct behavioral experiments without users' knowledge, changing what content they see to measure effects on mood. Users agreed to a general terms of service but were not specifically informed about the experiments. Is this ethically problematic?": "",
  "Yes, because specific informed consent for experimentation was not obtained, and the experiment could cause psychological harm": "",
  "No, because users agreed to the terms of service": "",
  "No, because companies are exempt from research ethics": "",
  "Yes, but only if the company is publicly traded": "",
  "General terms of service do not constitute informed consent for specific experiments, especially those that may affect participants' emotional well-being. This mirrors concerns raised by Facebook's 2014 emotional contagion study.": "",
  "A graduate student is running behind on her dissertation deadline. She has collected data from 180 of her planned 200 participants. Rather than recruit more participants, she fabricates data for 20 fictional participants with results similar to her existing data. What ethical violations has she committed?": "",
  "Data fabrication, which is scientific fraud regardless of whether the fake data matches real patterns": "",
  "None, because the fabricated data is similar to the real data": "",
  "Only a minor procedural violation": "",
  "An ethical violation only if she gets caught": "",
  "Fabricating data is scientific fraud regardless of the reason or how plausible the fake data appears. It undermines the integrity of the entire research enterprise and can lead to retraction, loss of credentials, and legal consequences.": "",
  "A clinical trial for a new cancer drug shows the drug is significantly extending lives compared to the placebo group. The trial is scheduled to run for two more years. An independent data safety monitoring board recommends stopping the trial early. Why would they make this recommendation?": "",
  "To prevent the drug from being approved by regulatory agencies before all required phases are completed": "",
  "To save money on the trial since the remaining two years of funding could be redirected to other research": "",
  "Because two more years is too long for any study and diminishing returns make extended data collection unnecessary": "",
  "Because continuing to give placebos when the treatment is clearly effective would be unethical (denying effective treatment to the control group)": "",
  "The principle of beneficence requires that once a treatment is clearly shown to be effective, it would be unethical to continue denying it to the control group. Data safety boards can recommend early termination.": "",
  "A researcher conducts 20 different statistical tests on the same dataset and finds one significant result (p = 0.04). She publishes only this one finding without mentioning the other 19 tests. What ethical and statistical problems does this present?": "",
  "The only problem is that she should have used a stricter threshold such as p = 0.01 to account for multiple comparisons": "",
  "This is standard practice in all scientific fields, since researchers routinely publish only their strongest individual findings": "",
  "No problem, because p = 0.04 is below the standard alpha level of 0.05 and therefore qualifies as statistically significant": "",
  "P-hacking and selective reporting: with 20 tests, finding one significant result by chance is expected, and hiding the other tests misrepresents the findings": "",
  "With 20 independent tests at alpha = 0.05, there is approximately a 64% chance of at least one false positive. Reporting only the significant result and hiding the failed tests is both p-hacking and selective reporting.": "",
  "A medical study in a developing country tests a new malaria treatment by giving the experimental drug to local villagers and comparing their outcomes to untreated villagers. The same study design would never be approved in the researchers' home country because a standard treatment exists. What ethical principle from the Belmont Report is being violated?": "",
  "Reproducibility, because the study design cannot be repeated under identical conditions in a different geographic location": "",
  "No principle is violated if the local government approves, since national sovereignty overrides international research guidelines": "",
  "Confidentiality, because villagers in small communities can easily be identified from the published research data": "",
  "Justice, because the burdens of research are being placed on a vulnerable population that would not benefit from the research design used in wealthier countries": "",
  "The principle of justice requires that research burdens and benefits be distributed fairly. Conducting a study in a developing country that would be considered unethical at home exploits a vulnerable population.": "",
  "A technology company collects location data, browsing history, and health app data from users' phones. They anonymize the data by removing names, then sell it to advertisers. A researcher later demonstrates that combining the 'anonymous' datasets can re-identify 87% of individuals. What does this reveal about anonymization?": "",
  "Companies have no obligation to protect user data": "",
  "Removing names alone may not be sufficient for true anonymization when other data points can be combined to re-identify individuals": "",
  "Anonymization is always completely effective": "",
  "87% re-identification is an acceptable rate": "",
  "Simply removing names does not guarantee anonymity. Combining multiple data points (location patterns, browsing habits, health data) can uniquely identify individuals, demonstrating that true anonymization requires more sophisticated techniques.": ""
